{"cursor":"2362","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"[[File:Vensundara2.jpg|thumb|120px| Ajahn Sundara ]]'[[Ajahn]] Sundara' is a\nFrench-born ordained monastic in the Buddhist Thai Forest Tradition of Ajahn\nChah. She studied dance (contemporary dance) and worked as a dancer and dance\nteacher until her early thirties when she had the opportunity to meet Ajahn\nSumedho in England and to attend one of his dhamma talks and then a\nretreat. {{cite web\n| url=http://www.dharma.org/ij/archives/2001b/sundara.htm title=It Can be Very\n| Simple: An interview with Ajahn Sundara accessdate=2006-09-16\n|date=\n| work=Barre Center for Buddhist Studies| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/we-\n| b/20061014180050/http://www.dharma.org/ij/archives/2001b/sundara.htm|\n| archivedate= 14 October 2006 | deadurl= no}} She was one\n| of the first four women ordained by Ajahn Sumedho in 1979 as an anagarika\n| (eight precept novice) and in 1983 as a 10 precept nun.\n{{cite web\n| url=http://www.dhammatalks.org.uk/sundar.htm title=Biography accessdate=2006-09-\n| 16\n|date=\n| work=dhammatalks.org.uk |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/200605050533-\n| 20/http://www.dhammatalks.org.uk/sundar.htm \n| |archivedate = 2006-05-05}} After living at Chithurst Monastery in\n| England, Ajahn Sundara moved in 1984 to Amaravati Buddhist Monastery and was\n| instrumental in founding the nuns' community there. She went to Thailand in\n| the mid-1990s, where she spent more than two years, primarily on retreat at\n| forest monasteries. She has been teaching and leading retreats in Europe and\n| North America for 20 years. She currently resides at Amaravati Buddhist\n| Monastery.\n","linknr":435,"url":"Ajahn_Sundara","recorded":1375060879,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Ajahn_Sundara&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Ajahn_Sundara&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-